Author-Name: HARRISON HONG 
Author-Name: JOSÉ SCHEINKMAN 
Author-Name: WEI XIONG 
Title: Asset Float and Speculative Bubbles 
Abstract:
 We model the relationship between asset float (tradeable shares) and
 speculative bubbles. Investors with heterogeneous beliefs and short-sales
 constraints trade a stock with limited float because of insider lockups. A
 bubble arises as price overweighs optimists' beliefs and investors
 anticipate the option to resell to those with even higher valuations. The
 bubble's size depends on float as investors anticipate an increase in
 float with lockup expirations and speculate over the degree of insider
 selling. Consistent with the internet experience, the bubble, turnover,
 and volatility decrease with float and prices drop on the lockup
 expiration date. Copyright 2006 by The American Finance Association. 
